Cyclists, hikers, and birders can now enjoy the accessible Adirondack Rail Trail in New York. The old railway route provides visitors with multiple connecting trails to explore and an opportunity to visit the small communities and serene spots found along the way, like Lake Placid.   
The 34-mile Adirondack Rail Trailâ€”for cyclists, hikers, and birdersâ€”winds through open wilderness while connecting scenic towns like Lake Placid, Tupper Lake, and Saranac Lake.&nbsp;

The Adirondack Rail Trailâ€”which follows the oldÂ Remsen-Lake Rail corridorÂ is a 34-mile accessible path that runs through the heart ofÂ Adirondack ParkÂ in New York State. Two-thirds (25 miles) of the trail is open to bikers, runners, hikers, and birders, providing access to breathtaking trails, numerous campsites, and waterwayâ€¦

